{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3483360,"name":"Evan Sigl","username":"Legomonster33","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/legomonster33/{size}/234529_2.png","created_at":"2025-01-15T15:07:31.146Z","cooked":"

What originally started as a personal challenge of cadding a robot for REEFSCAPE in 24 hours, quickly turned into cadding a robot in a more reasonable amount of time. I was inspired by @howlongismyname doing the same thing last year and this year and took it as a personal goal to cad a robot as quickly as I could.

And so: I present my 2025 REEFSCAPE Robot: WISP
Onshape Link

WISP7009×4955 10.5 MB

Archetype Overview

Archetype7009×4955 4.56 MB

  • Front mount elevator with a funnel to intake coral from hp

  • Laterator to extend the coral mech to the reef

  • Algae intake on the back

  • Deep climb integrated into the algae intake

Robot Specifications

  • 110lbs dry weight, 140lbs fully loaded

  • Mk4i Swerve

  • 11’’ COG Height

  • Drop chassis with 3/16" ground clearance

  • 16 Motors

  • Designed with manufacturing in mind, the only hard-to-make parts are the bent polycarb and the tube support blocks on the climber.

  • Keeps cost down, this robot uses only NEO motors and common COTS items

  • Uses a common plate thickness, Every aluminum plate is 1/8 thick except for the bumper brackets

  • Counterbalanced elevator with Constant force springs: Increases cycle times and reduces needed gearing on the drive motors

Robot Capabilities

  • L1 to L4 coral, theoretical cycle times < 1 second (after drivebase lines up)

  • Removes algae from the reef with an integrated roller on the end effector

  • Ground intake algae to score in the proccessor

  • Human player intake Coral, Funnel means you don’t have to line up

Match Strategy

AUTO:

Goal: Maximize points earned

  • Cycle L1-4 Coral as fast as possible

TELEOP:

Goal: Maximize Rp earned via coral and algae scoring

  • Cycle L1-4 Coral while removing all algae from the reef

  • Once the reef is free of algae you can switch to algae cleanup or continue cycling coral

ENDGAME:

Goal: Guarantee Barge RP without relying on teammates to climb

  • Continue cycling coral or algae as long as possible

  • Deep climb at the last possible moment, the intake geometry means it’s easy to line up

Strategic design

When kickoff happened I immediately started thinking about what the most effective ways to play the game would be and considered all aspects of the game
I decided that my ideal robot would be able to:

  • ground algae
  • processor algae
  • l1-4 Coral
  • HP intake coral
  • Deep climb

Notable things that I deemed unimportant or unnecessary:

  • net algae - avoid the extra complexity to lift or shoot the balls
  • ground coral - 2 hp stations per side mean its unlikely that ground pickup is the only option
  • shallow climb - deep climb is easier and worth more points
  • controlled reef algae - removing algae from the reef without controlling it means the end effector can be far simpler

These strategic choices allowed for a competitive robot without sacrificing performance for unneeded complexity and drove the design of my robot.
I’m not trying to make the best robot but I am trying to make a robot that i think would be fun to drive. a complex robot that is impossible to drive isn’t fun for anyone involved.

Mechanism Overviews

WISP has 7 Major subsystems.

Drivebase

30x30 Mk4i Square with a 1/8" bellypan

Drivebase7009×4955 6.07 MB

  • Mk4i swerve

  • 30x30 frame

  • 0.35" bumper gap

  • motor controller holders and handles integrated into swerve covers

  • 20lbs bumpers for ballast

End Effector

2 parallel rollers to grab coral from the funnel.

Coral Holder7009×4955 5.53 MB

Details

  • n550 + ultraplanetary for power

  • cantilevered wheels means you can score coral by just pulling the elevator down

  • passive wrist attaches to laterator for more flexible scoring

  • Algae removal roller

  • 3.7lbs

Laterator

integrated into the elevator carriage for ease of assembly, provides the needed motion to score coral.

Laterator7009×4955 4.67 MB

Details

  • sprocket rack for power

  • passive wrist to mount the end effector

  • integrates right into the elevator carriage

  • unpowered linkage for wiring, inspired by docking drawers

Elevator

Belt In tube continuous rigging for super easy rigging and Cf springs for smooth fast motion.

Elevator4956×7009 5.66 MB

Details

  • Belt in tube continuous Rigging

  • Constant force springs to counterbalance

  • Cf springs are rigged to Dyneema, keeping them closer to the bottom for better COG

  • Direct drive with 2 Motors (the cf springs allow this)

Algae Intake

Slapdown intake to allow easy integration with the climber while maintaining efficient algae grabbing

Algae Intake7009×4955 7.39 MB

Details

  • 125:1 pivot gearing

  • dual motor for pivot

  • integrated climber

  • full width, touch it, own it

  • geometry is easy to line up for the climb

Climb

Inspired by Rusthounds RI3D, packages nicely in the intake and a central COG means the robot can hang a few inches from the ground

Climber7009×4955 6.61 MB

climbing4956×7009 4.16 MB

Details

  • Leadscrew actuated

  • billet aluminum blocks hold the pipes

  • the pipes could be knurled or to increase grip on the cage

Funnel

Centers corals after receiving them from the loading station so that the end effector can grab them consistently.

Funnel7009×4955 5.65 MB

Details
  • Its a funnel

Passive Wrist

Attaches the end effector to the laterator to allow efficient coral scoring

Wrist7009×4955 5.33 MB

Details

  • rotates between 0 - 70 degrees

  • automatically angles the end effector to match the reef while scoring

  • live axle hex


Cycles:

combining the passive writst, laterator, elevator, and the end effector allows for efficient coral scoring cycles, while the algae mechanism scoops up algae in the meantime.

Coral on the reef:

Step 1: The robot is in starting configuration

Starting Config7009×4955 6.5 MB

Step 2: The Algae mechanism deploys to make way for the laterator as the elevator starts going up

Intake Deploys7009×4955 6.54 MB

Step 3: The elevator goes up to the desired scoring level 1-4

Elevator Goes Up4956×7009 3.32 MB

Step 4: The laterator extends to line up the coral with the reef

lateratorExtends4956×7009 3.27 MB

Step 5: The elevator starts coming down, and the algae catches on the reef

Elevator Comes Down7009×4955 3.04 MB

Step 6: The elevator keeps going down, the passive wrist allows the coral to line up right onto the reef

Wrist In Full Motion7009×4955 2.87 MB

Step 7: The elevator keeps going down and the laterator starts retracting, Pulling the coral out of the gripper.

Scored The Coral7009×4955 3.07 MB

Step 8: The laterator fully retracts, the passive wrist flops back down to the neutral position

laterator Retracted7009×4955 3.01 MB

Step 9: The coral has been scored and the robot is now ready to intake a new one from the HP station

Details

Recieving Coral From HP Station:

Step 1: The robot is in starting Configuration

Starting Config No Coral7009×4955 6.95 MB

Step 2: The Algae mechanism deploys to make way for the laterator as the elevator starts going up

Intake Deploys7009×4955 6.54 MB

Step 3: The elevator goes above the chute, out of the way of the incoming coral

Elevator Moves Up7009×4955 3.12 MB

Step 4: The human player hucks the coral into the funnel

HP Feeds7009×4955 2.96 MB

Step 5: The funnel Catches the coral

Funnel Catches7009×4955 3.27 MB

Step 6: The funnel re-orients the coral for pickup, The elevator starts coming down.

Funnel Reorients4956×7009 4.19 MB

Step 7: The elevator comes down fully, allowing the end effector to grab the coral

Grabs The Coral4956×7009 3.96 MB

Step 8: The coral has been acquired, and the robot can now proceed with scoring it.

Algae Removal From The Reef:

Step 1: The elevator and laterator move the end effector into position

Algae Removal7009×4955 3.28 MB

Step 2: The elevator drives the end effector upwards into the coral, The roller spins Counterclockwise to spin the algae against the reef

Algae Removal Electric Boogaloo7009×4955 3.33 MB

Step 3: The algae continues out of the reef and tumbles onto the floor:

Algae Tumbles Away7009×4955 3.98 MB

Step 4: The elevator and laterator return to the stowed config

Starting Config7009×4955 6.95 MB

Details

The Climb:

Step 1: End effector is put into the climb position while the driver lines up with the cage

Robot in Position7009×4955 3.57 MB

Step 2: The climber pipe is driven across using the leadscrew

Pipe Is Driven Across7009×4955 8.07 MB

Step 3: Once the pipe is fully across, the intake can begin rotating

Intake Rotates7009×4955 3.43 MB

Step 4: The intake rotates the rest of the way, lifting the robot

Robot has Climbed4956×7009 3.56 MB

Center of Mass877×1122 186 KB

Details

Challenges Faced:

throughout the time designing WISP, I faced some challenges, mainly integrating all the mechanisms while still leaving room for deep climb and the laterator. as well as trying to make weight.

Looking back:

if I were to do this again I would spend more time picking an archetype, as I don’t believe that combining the algae and climber mechanisms was the wisest choice.

Future improvements

Things to add:

  • Vision system
  • Cable chain on the elevator Added
  • Hardstops on the wrist
  • Better breaker placement
  • Battery wires

I hope that by sharing this I inspire you this season! If you have any questions or comments, please feel free to post here or contact me directly.

shoutout to @AntPoison for helping with the writing and formatting
